================================
CATEGORY 3: BEHAVIORAL PATTERNS
================================
DEFINITION:
Behavioral patterns are concerned with algorithms and the assignment of 
responsibilities between objects. They describe not just patterns of 
objects or classes, but the patterns of communication between them.

CORE GOALS:
- Define how objects "talk" to one another.
- Reduce direct "coupling" (dependency) between communicating objects.
- Abstract the logic of a process so it can be changed at runtime.

COFFEE SHOP CONTEXT:
This is the "Social Logic" of the shop. How does a customer know their 
drink is ready? (Observer/Notification). How does the manager coordinate 
the Barista and the Janitor so they don't crash into each other? (Mediator). 
How do you decide to pay with Cash versus Phone? (Strategy). These 
patterns handle the "Behavior" and "Flow" of the shop's operations.